{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Overflow","slug":"css-overflow","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"10 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Height and Width"],"learning_objectives":["Control content that is too big to fit","Understand overflow: visible","Understand overflow: hidden","Understand overflow: scroll","Understand overflow: auto"],"theory":"The `overflow` property specifies what happens if content overflows an element's box.\n\n*   `visible`: Default. Overflow is not clipped. It renders outside the element's box.\n*   `hidden`: The overflow is clipped, and the rest of the content will be invisible.\n*   `scroll`: The overflow is clipped, but a scrollbar is added to see the rest of the content.\n*   `auto`: Similar to scroll, but it adds scrollbars only when necessary.","syntax":"div {\n  width: 200px;\n  height: 50px;\n  overflow: auto;\n}","examples":[{"code":".card {\n  width: 200px;\n  height: 100px;\n  overflow: hidden;\n}","output":"Any text inside .card that exceeds 100px height is cut off.","explanation":"Used to maintain strict grid layouts where cards must be uniform size."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using scroll on mobile","correction":"Mobile browsers handle `auto` well, but creating nested scrollbars acts poorly for UX.","example":""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"How do you handle text overflow with '...'?","answer":"Use `text-overflow: ellipsis;` along with `white-space: nowrap;` and `overflow: hidden;`.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Create a box that shows a scrollbar only if the text is too long.","hint":"Use overflow: auto.","solution":"overflow: auto;","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Chat Windows","description":"Chat interfaces use `overflow-y: scroll` on the message container to allow scrolling through history while keeping the input box fixed.","code":".chat-history { height: 400px; overflow-y: auto; }"}],"exam_notes"